<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF76FE21FD26FE20" blockId="54.[151,1437,423,1171]" box="[151,710,423,449]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Size. Known adult size about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F03FF94FE07FE21FDD9FE20" box="[486,569,423,449]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" unit="cm" value="8.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="7.0">7–9 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F03FF94FF26FE4DFB5EFB70" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26FE4DFD1BFD78" blockId="54.[151,1437,423,1171]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Morphology. D V–VI + I,12–14; A I,11–13; P 15–18. Relatively small goby. Snout short and with a steep profile. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. Dorsal fins of similar height; first dorsal fin with a relatively rounded shape, the 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FE11FD95FC5AFDCC" bold="true" box="[496,954,530,557]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">dorsal spines often slightly prolonged</emphasis>
(membranes slightly incised between the spines); 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FF16FDB0FE4AFD94" bold="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">in breeding males, both dorsal fins have prolonged free tips on spines and rays, and deeply incised interradial membranes</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F03FF94FE59FDDDFDEBFD94" box="[440,523,603,629]" captionStart="FIGURE 42" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1078,1102]" captionTargetBox="[204,1382,181,1054]" captionTargetId="figure-19@38.[204,1382,181,1054]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 42. One black spot on the corner of the mouth, usually followed by two elongated dots on ventral border of the cheek (all marked with arrows) in G. couchi. Photo by M. Kovačić." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601701/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
). Caudal fin rounded. Scales present on body and on predorsal area, usually visible on photographs, at least on body (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F03FF94FDF3FDF9FD0FFD78" author="Renoult, J. P. &amp; Pillon, R. &amp; Kovacic, M. &amp; Louisy, P." box="[530,751,639,665]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref63723" refString="Renoult, J. P., Pillon, R., Kovacic, M. &amp; Louisy, P. (2022) Frontiers in Fishwatching Series - Gobies of North-eastern Atlantic and the Mediterranean: Gobius and Thorogobius. Les cahiers de la fondation Biotope. [in press]" type="book" year="2022">
Renoult 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FD92FDF9FD44FD78" box="[627,676,639,665]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">et al</emphasis>
. 2022
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26FD25FB25FCE4" blockId="54.[151,1437,423,1171]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FE68FD25FB2AFD5C" bold="true" box="[393,1226,674,701]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Body gray, light brown or olive with mottled or reticulated pattern</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F03FF94FB3CFD25FAD6FD5C" box="[1245,1334,675,701]" captionStart="FIGURE 43" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,1163,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-57@38.[203,1385,1163,1951]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 43. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius couchi. Photo by R. Pillon, Rab Island, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601705" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601705/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
). Lateral midline is always darker, formed by a longitudinal series of small black spots. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FC1CFD40FBB4FCE4" bold="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">One black spot on the corner of the mouth, usually followed by 2 more or less rectangular dark spots on lower cheek</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F03FF94FB85FD6DFB58FCE4" box="[1124,1208,747,773]" captionStart="FIGURE 42" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1078,1102]" captionTargetBox="[204,1382,181,1054]" captionTargetId="figure-19@38.[204,1382,181,1054]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 42. One black spot on the corner of the mouth, usually followed by two elongated dots on ventral border of the cheek (all marked with arrows) in G. couchi. Photo by M. Kovačić." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601701/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26FC89FDF9FCC8" blockId="54.[151,1437,423,1171]" box="[199,537,783,809]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F03FF94FE9EFC89FDF2FCC9" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[383,530,783,809]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FE9EFC89FDF2FCC9" box="[383,530,783,809]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Gobius niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F03FF94FF26FCB5FCABFC74" blockId="54.[151,1437,423,1171]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Habitat. Infralittoral species, known from 
<quantity id="2E379B383F03FF94FD54FCB5FCEFFCAC" box="[693,783,819,845]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" unit="m" value="10.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="1.0">1–20 m</quantity>
depth on soft bottoms with algae or marine plants and shelters such as rocks and holes. In the Mediterranean, it is generally found in sheltered bays, often associated with 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F03FF94FF76FCFDFE93FC74" box="[151,371,891,917]" class="Liliopsida" family="Cymodoceaceae" genus="Cymodocea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nodosa">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FF76FCFDFE93FC74" box="[151,371,891,917]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Cymodocea nodosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F03FF94FE63FCFDFDB5FC74" author="Pillon, R. &amp; Poncet, S. &amp; Louisy, P." box="[386,597,891,917]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref63148" refString="Pillon, R., Poncet, S. &amp; Louisy, P. (2016 b) Signalisation de / Record of Gobius couchi, 18 August 2016 (obs. 27 May 2016, photo  2425). Fish Watch Forum, Louisy, P. &amp; Francour, P. (Ed.). Available from: https: // www. fish-watch. org (accessed 28 September 2021)" type="url" year="2016">
Pillon 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F03FF94FE2CFCFDFE1FFC74" box="[461,511,891,917]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">et al</emphasis>
. 2016 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F03FF94FDA6FCFDFDB5FC74" author="Kesici, N. B. &amp; Dalyan, C." box="[583,597,891,917]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="8 - 10" refId="ref57275" refString="Kesici, N. B. &amp; Dalyan, C. (2019) New record of the zebra goby, Zebrus zebrus (Risso, 1827), in the Bosphorus Strait (Turkey). Turkish Journal of Bioscience and Collections, 3 (1), 8 - 10. https: // doi. org / 10.26650 / tjbc. 20190002" type="journal article" year="2019">b</bibRefCitation>
